(1605, '_transient_dash_4077549d03da2e451c8b5f002294ff51', '<div class="rss-widget"><ul><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wordpress.org/news/2014/03/wordpress-3-9-beta-2/'' title=''WordPress 3.9 Beta 2 is now available forÂ testing! Weâ€™ve made more than a hundred changes since Beta 1, but we still need your help if weâ€™re going to hit our goal of an April release. For what to look out for, please head on over toÂ the Beta 1 announcement post. Some of the changes in [â€¦]''>WordPress 3.9 Beta 2</a> <span class="rss-date">March 20, 2014</span><div class=''rssSummary''>WordPress 3.9 Beta 2 is now available forÂ testing! Weâ€™ve made more than a hundred changes since Beta 1, but we still need your help if weâ€™re going to hit our goal of an April release. For what to look out for, please head on over toÂ the Beta 1 announcement post. Some of the changes in [â€¦]</div></li></ul></div><div class="rss-widget"><ul><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wptavern.com/monster-widget-a-useful-wordpress-theme-testing-tool?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=monster-widget-a-useful-wordpress-theme-testing-tool'' title=''Activating and deactivating widgets can become quite tedious when testing WordPress themes. Monster Widget is a handy plugin, created by the folks at Automattic. It adds all of the default WordPress widgets to a â€œmonsterâ€ widget that you can deploy as one collective instance. Monster Widget Once the widget is added to your sidebar, youâ€™ll see all of the following standard core widgets on the frontend:   Archives List and Dropdown Calendar Categories List and Drowpdown Pages Meta Recent Comments Recent Posts RSS Search Text (with images and text) Tag Cloud Nav Menu Blogroll  If youâ€™re creating a WordPress theme for public distribution or for a client, the Monster Widget will give you an instant picture of how different kinds of widgets will display in your theme. Once youâ€™re done testing, you can easily remove all of the widgets in one click. The plugin was not created for production use but can save you quite a bit of time (at least a couple dozen clicks) during theme development and testing. Download the Monster Widget plugin from WordPress.org.''>WPTavern: Monster Widget: A Useful WordPress Theme Testing Tool</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wptavern.com/wordpress-security-plugin-roundtable-on-upcoming-episode-of-wpweekly?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=wordpress-security-plugin-roundtable-on-upcoming-episode-of-wpweekly'' title=''Earlier this month, we interviewed Dre Armeda and Tony Perez of Sucuri.net to talk about WordPress security. Both guests shared information from a services perspective. We received a lot of positive feedback on the amount information presented in the episode. Weâ€™re going to turn the tables and discuss securing WordPress from the perspective of using plugins. photo credit: Stuck in Customs â€“ cc On Friday April 4th, weâ€™ll be hosting a WordPress security plugin roundtable. Guests scheduled to appear are:  Chris Wiegman â€“ Lead Developer of iThemes Security Regina Smola â€“ Founder of WPSecurityLock Brennen Byrne â€“ Founder and CEO of Clef Sam Hotchkiss â€“ Founder of BruteProtect  The goal of this episode is to inform users what security plugins are capable of and why you shouldnâ€™t be afraid to use them. Weâ€™ll also cover a wide range of good security practices you should be aware of. The guests are monitoring the comments on this post and will answer any questions you have about their plugins or services.''>WPTavern: WordPress Security Plugin Roundtable On Upcoming Episode Of WPWeekly</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wptavern.com/blogging-tip-how-to-link-to-a-dubious-website-without-improving-its-seo?utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=blogging-tip-how-to-link-to-a-dubious-website-without-improving-its-seo'' title=''photo credit: opacity â€“ cc In the course of blogging about important issues, there are times when you may need to link to dubious or objectionable material in order to provide context for your post. For example, some subject matter may necessitate a reference to racist material or a fraudulent business. Unfortunately, when it comes to SEO, the age old maxim â€œAny press is good pressâ€ still proves to be true. By linking to a dubious website you are involuntarily strengthening the siteâ€™s position in search engines. If you donâ€™t want to be complicit in promoting a site of ill-repute, thereâ€™s a service that you can use to deny these sites the SEO benefits of your link. Donotlink is a site where you can paste in links to shady websites and receive a custom URL that will not not improve their search engine rankings.  It works in a similar way to your standard url shorteners, except that it goes one step further to route questionable links through a unique intermediate URL which then forwards the visitor to the final destination via Javascript. Donotlink employs three additional methods to prevent search engines from crawling the questionable site:  Blocks the URL in its robots.txt file, so (search engine) robots are discouraged from crawling it Adds the â€œnofollowâ€ attribute to the link If a known robot decides to crawl the link, Donotlink will identify it and serve it a blank page (403 Forbidden) instead of redirecting to the url.  Who might use donotlink? The site offers a few secenarios wherein one might consider using the service: Skeptics, bloggers, journalists and friends on social media use donotlink to link to scams, pseudoscience, misinformation, alternative medicine, conspiracy theories, racist / sexist blog posts, etc. without improving the search engine position of the site they are discussing. If you want to use the service but donâ€™t want to be bothered to visit the site each time, you can structure your URL like so: http://www.donotlink.com/www.example.com/shady/stuff.html If youâ€™re linking to questionable material quite often or simply want to take a principled stand against the spread of misinformation, Donotlink is an easy way to prevent your site from sending â€œGoogle juiceâ€ to the bad guys. This seems like it would be an easy WordPress plugin to create and could be useful for publications that help bring attention to shady practices.''>WPTavern: Blogging Tip: How to Link to a Dubious Website Without Improving Its SEO</a></li></ul></div><div class="rss-widget"><ul><li class=''dashboard-news-plugin''><span>Popular Plugin:</span> <a href=''http://wordpress.org/plugins/ml-slider/'' class=''dashboard-news-plugin-link''>Meta Slider</a></h5>&nbsp;<span>(<a href=''plugin-install.php?tab=plugin-information&amp;plugin=ml-slider&amp;_wpnonce=a4b3c487ba&amp;TB_iframe=true&amp;width=600&amp;height=800'' class=''thickbox'' title=''Meta Slider''>Install</a>)</span></li></ul></div>', 'no'),
